remixed_from.title: Tacblade Utility Stanley Blade Folding Knife

description.text:
The "Tacblade Utility Stanley Blade Folding Knife" was a fine design. But, sadly print orientation, infill percentage, and just differences in material can make that fine design not work as well. To overcome the plasticity and warping that can occur with PLA, I added some changes to the both the inner blade holding mechanism and the outer handle.

When cutting some strapping I had the razor blade fly out to sail across the room. Under pressure the blade was able to separate the two halves and fly out.. To help prevent this, I put a "snapping tab" on one side to hold both inner parts together better. A tiny amount of sanding is needed to get the snap to fit, but doing in that way means it will snap together tight no matter how ist was printed, but still come apart to change blades.

Second, because PLA can warp (see images), I made the lower outer handle have a notch the rises up through the top outer handle. That notch ensures the two parts do no slip past each other, and if the handle does warp it still has enough height to not matter.

comments.text:
I like the snap-fit part - that was one of the things I didn't like about the original.
If I might suggest: instead of merely extending the post thru the top plate, how about modifying the top plate to have a (underslung) horizontal tab which fits into a horizontal slot in the bottom plate's end? There's plenty of clearance for this approach, and that way the outer plates are firmly constrained at both ends.

The original metal grid of my Makerbot Replicator are mounted at one side of the fan with another side free in the air.  They generate a low frequency "hum" due to the free ends and the elasticity of the metal.  This honey comb grid was produced targeting the elimination of the low frequency hum and give it a cool look.  
This honey comb grid will generate a higher pitch sound.  Due to increased blockage, it will reduce the cooling effectiveness so a higher flow rate fan may be considered to go with it.  
It is optimized for 0.4 mm nozzle, with most structures of the honey comb being 0.8mm.

title: modular x-carriage - next level: MGN12 linear guide x-axis

description.text:
As a new upgrade to get the tevo tarantula and my dual-hotend-setup ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2172765 ) working on full bed size I made a decision: redesign my x-axis.

This contains a MGN12 linear guide.

To get it working with this higher position in comparison to the bottom edge of the extrusion, you have to use a 4mm-dropped module (v4-version).
Due to the no longer used wheels on the carriage it is possible to use the normal-sized integrated fan, without the expansion on the fan's side.

This part's modular carriage is shifted backwards as much as possible. There remains a gap between the right fan and the extrusion of round about 7mm. That could crash into a possible x-axis-motor-mount on the right of the axis! With the full design of my future x-axis there is no crash expected (height is 6mm).

all other files available at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2158837.

stay tuned for z- and x-axis-parts

x-axis carriage:

The basic component takes the hotend modules. 4 M3-screw-holes to mount it to the MGN12 miniature guide carriage and next to that 2 holes as a central point for possible addons (cable chain, fan connectors)
It's slightly of larger width then he HIWIN MGN12H carriage (~ 45mm) to trigger the x-endstop.
There are 2 versions per each type of MGN12: long and short. The shorter one takes the entire hotend module by 4mm towards the extrusion,
but: IT DOESN'T FIT WITH DUAL INTEGRATED FAN on my designed printer rework. The left fan cover ("HOT!") would crash into the x-idler.

x-carriage-modules:
because of the higher MGN12 linear rail (13mm in comparison to 3mm) the modules needs to be lowered by 4, better 8 mm (V5). Used 4mm first and the extrusion hit the rear heated bed glass clamp. There was a gap of 2.5mm.

X-axis future design (the overlap of the carriage is removed as you can confirm in the STL-file), but it would never run into the extrusion right hotend touches bed on the left, left hotend on the right: perfectly used bed width

title: Canees - "Cane" like device for blind dogs / Dispositivo para perros ciegos

description.text:
This easy-to-make device acts as a cane for blind dogs. It lets them feel tactile feedback when they're about to hit something on their way. It can be adjusted to any dog size, but it works better for smaller dogs.

The model must be mirrored to have a left piece and right piece.

Materials and instructions can be found below.

Este dispositivo fácil de fabricar funciona como un bastón para perros ciegos. Les permite recibir un estímulo táctil cuando estén por golpearse con algo en su camino. El dispositivo puede ajustarse a cualquier tamaño de perro.

Es necesario espejear el modelo para imprimir las piezas izquierda y derecha.

La lista de materiales e instrucciones se encuentran abajo.

Materiales

-Piezas izquierda y derecha impresas
-Collar de cuero de 4mm de espesor de la talla del perro
-Alambre multiuso Dand-o-Line marca Hillman

Paso 1

Retira cualquier exceso de plástico que pueda quedar en la superficie de las piezas para permitir que el collar y el alambre entren y para evitarle molestias al perro.

Desliza el collar por los orificios rectangulares de las piezas. Debes cuidar el orden en que los pones, pues los dos canales para el alambre deben apuntar hacia frente. Las piezas deberían permanecer firmes, pero ajustables.

Paso 2

Corta el alambre con una longitud que permita hacer un "halo" alrededor de la cabeza de tu perro.

Con una cuchilla quita el recubrimiento del alambre unos 12cm de cada extremo.

Introduce los extremos del alambre en su respectivo canal en las piezas impresas.

Paso 3

Con unas pinzas dobla las puntas del alambre de tal manera que apunten hacia adelante. Usando silicón caliente fija todo a las piezas impresas, esto evitará que el halo se mueva demasiado y que el perro se lastime con las puntas del alambre.

Moldea el alambre para darle forma redonda u ovalada. Es posible que esta forma cambie o se mueva con el uso, especialmente si el perro es grande, así que tendrás que ajustarlo de vez en cuando.

Paso 4

Ponle el collar al perro lo más ajustado que puedas y ya está listo para andar.

El dispositivo no es invasivo, pesado ni incómodo, pero el perro requerirá de un tiempo para acostumbrarse a usarlo. Una vez que se acostumbre se salvará de más de un golpe en la pared.

The two holes should be tapped for M5 screws and bolted to the end-plates. This document describes how to connect limit switches to grbl. Here's a video of the switches in action! Edit

title: Carved Taino Shaman from Dominican Republic
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is a carving of an Taino shaman figurine. The Taino are the indigenous people of the Caribbean. At the time of European contact in the late 15th century, they were the principal inhabitants of most of Cuba, Trinidad, Jamaica, Hispaniola (Haiti and the Dominican Republic), and Puerto Rico.

Shamans and spirituality were central to the Taino culture, and these figurines are representative of that culture. This shows a typical 'holy man', or shaman, in a squatting position, with the hollow portions showing the stylized depiction of emanciation due to starving oneself for religous enlightenment.

This is carved out of Guayacan (Ironwood) wood, the hardest wood in the world, and will easily sink in water. One of the most popular souvenirs from the D.R are figures made from Guayacan wood.

This was hand made and purchased from a local craftsman in the early 2000's during an archaeological expedition near Santiago de los Caballeros, Dominican Republic.

Enjoy this scan, see reference photos if you wish to paint it.

Please post a photo to share if you print this, and check out my other scans of skulls and bones at http://www.thingiverse.com/dricketts/designs.
Be sure to "Like" my Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/FetalReproductions to subscribe to my current prints/blogs, and see my Etsy page at http://Etsy.com/FetalReproductions for baby fetal scans, skulls, and other items to own.

Purpose built to allow an automated system to water small plants using an external pump and reservoir. While this was designed for a specific project, TwitchGrowsPlants, it should be usable for any small plant that can use a reservoir to wick from, and for which monitoring/metering of watering is desired. A 10cc syringe with the needle removed is used in the holder. A small bit of superglue around the area it meets the holder was required to stop it from leaking, even though it has a snug fit. The syringes are Nipro 20Gx1" (10ml), and can be found on ebay and elsewhere online.

The two holes in the bottom of the planter should be used to feed and tie a wick in whose end will sit in the reservoir below. For my project, I used some 550 paracord with a knot on either end of the hole.

For the reservoir, the v4 (long version) shelves require supports. For now, I have shortened the tank in the newer version, and added chamfered edges below the shelves to require less or no supports. There is still a long bridge across the middle, so it may be worth testing to ensure you can print a long bridge before attempting without supports. It is also likely that I will reprint these in a transparent material or with provisions for a viewport to see water levels, so the design is likely to change again soon.

description.text:
My girlfriend is a Speech Pathologist that was tasked with creating a model Larynx for a graduate course. She was keen enough to remember that I had a 3D printer, and there might have been models floating around on the internet. Surely, she found one.

Seeing as to how my print settings are not in tune quite yet, I had trouble printing the whole model at once, as the vocal folds were being torn off by the supports generated between the model. Not to mention the sheer amount of supports necessary to print this. Having no knowledge of editing STL files, I tasked myself with breaking it up. Tinkercad allowed me to make 3 parts to this model which cut down on the supports tremendously.

The orientation of the files are what I found to be optimal for the least amount of support (rotate the vocal folds 90 degrees!). Some light touch up work is required; for instance, the Cricoid cartilage has some leftovers of the Thyroid Cartilige, but that's a breeze to take off.

The files are designed for the purpose of super gluing or hot gluing the parts together. Additionally, having 3 separate parts allows you to paint sections of the Larynx as she did in the pictures.

If anyone else happens to stumble upon this and would benefit from this in a classroom/medical environment, I hope this makes the process easier! Good luck!

I like to play Outpost, but it has a lot of cards and a huge number of cardboard tiles to deal with. In order to speed up setup, I created boxes to organize all the tiles and the production (money) cards.

My solution to organizing this game is as follows:

  1. Sleeve all the cards (large and small).
  2. Use Hugo's magic tape to bundle the following decks of cards:
    • Colony Upgrade cards
    • Kicker Expansion Colony Upgrade cards
    • Player Order cards
  3. Use my 3D printer to create boxes (with lids) for the following:
    • All of the factory counters and special factory counters
    • Colonist/Robot counters, Tracking counters, Dice
    • Small production cards (Ore, Water, Mega Water, Titanium, Mega Titanium)
    • Large production cards (all others)

The boxes fit flat in the center well, along with the card decks. The player boards sit above the card decks and counter boxes, and then the rule book sits above the player boards and the production card boxes. The box closes without any bulges or stresses.

In addition to the two production card boxes, I've included a single all-in-one production card box, but it is too large to print on most printers.

title: optimized Hair Filter for level access shower drain

description.text:
My Parents home was renewed and they have got a modern level-access shower.

The Drain area of this Shower is covered by some metal Frame Design cover.
To prevent blockage there is a Hair Filter placed under this cover.

The design of this Hair Filter is not very clever and it has to been cleaned each time after a shower. If it is not cleaned each time and there is a woman with long Hair in Household the filter will block and the drain will not work anymore.

Problem of actual Filter is that the openings are all on the same level and the Hairs will just lay over all openings consistent. In combination of foam, dirt, etc they build a sealant very fast.

I have build a filter with openings wich are rising to the middle and an bigger opening to bypass the smaler Openings as well as for the ventilation. The Hairs will sediment on the lower openings while the openings on higher level will still work.

Last week i have installed this Filter at my parents home and the feedback is actually positive.

title: LED bulb adapter for gothic lamp

description.text:
This is an adapter i designed in order to fit a regular LED bulb into the lamp and be able to use it as a regular lamp. The actual lamp can be found here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2395716 The whole thing is assembled using 4 #8 screws. I used a bottle lamp kit as it had everything i needed already, but all the pieces you need are a
power cord,
a threaded rod,
a "socket" for the bulb,
and the bulb itself.
Please use only LED bulbs with this as incandescent bulbs will heat up considerably and there is a risk on the lamp melting. Also this lamp should not be left unattended and you should avoid leaving it on at night for safety, I've let it stay on all day with a 100W LED bulb inside and the heat from the bulb did not affect the printed pieces in any way thanks to the space around the bulb and the openings which allow air to flow around it.

Purchased couple of flamenco dancer printed canvases from Spain few months ago, for which I didn't find suitable frames. Therefore I made this one, choosing the printer's triangular infill to add texture to the front of the frame.

It was challenging designing the frame that large for 3D printing, therefore, the puzzle connection hooks made it possible to print the frame parts even with small platform printers.

I didn't want to use glue or anything else to connect the frame parts tightly, therefore, I made a snug fit between the hooks to fine tune them with a sanding file upon assembly.

Printed the frame with wood filament.

Parts are aligned on the printer bed upside down as there is a 1mm space in the back for the canvas to fit in.

Therefore, if you want to have an infill patterns on the frame front, make sure to set your printer as follows:

  • Bottom layers (0) this is the front of the frame
  • Top layers (2) this is the back of the frame and the solid layers will hide the canvas edges
  • Wall (3) layers to have a solid connection amongst the parts

I also set the infill extrusion width to 150% to have thick infill lines.

If your software does not have a default setting for triangular infill, the setting for it is:

To get an interesting diamond patterns, just remove the zero.

description.text:
Hello! I've been wanting to find some pacman characters that are easy to print and color, and I've found the almost perfect ghost!
The original model belongs to StensethJeremy.

The reason why I did this was because I wanted to print, sand, and color the pacman characters to give as a gift to someone. But I couldn't find one with easy to color eyes, and I currently am just learning how to use Fusion 360, so I can't make my own yet.
So I did what I could, and decided to share it with anyone else who wants to do that!
Have fun, and thank you again StensethJeremy for creating the original model!

I've also made a version with 3mm cut off the bottom to give it flat feet to hopefully make it easier to get good print adhesion.
(This will be the version I will print)

Updates for me;
Sanding and acrylic spraying is done, and the picture is up!
Now I wait for paint to arrive. (I already sanded again)

I originally brought the model into Tinkercad, so I could just add a cylinder and half-sphere to fill in the model, then use a roof to cut out the feet. (Found out that there are 12 feet, 15 degrees apart from each other)
I thought this would be just perfect! But it wasn't. In cura the half-sphere didn't work correctly with the head of the ghost, so I instead this this;

I brought the model into Blender so I can delete all of the inside faces, then made a top and bottom face so that there'd only be one skin for the whole model.
Then I brought it into Tinkercad, and used a cylinder to find out where the half-sphere needed to start. After that I messed with the size of the half-sphere so that it wouldn't poke out of the ghost, or mess up the eyes, then joined them together and made a correctly printable model!

It's still not perfect, but since I'm going to sand it and paint it, I'm okay with the slight outline there will be where the hole in the head used to be.

description.text:
ATTENTION: Maiden flight shows the thrust angle is wrong, will update soon.

DeHavilland Mosquito.

Original 3d model: https://grabcad.com/library/de-havilland-dh-98-mosquito-1

Wingspan- 600mm
Weight of printed parts- 310g

Work in progress, if you print it and fly it, give some feedback, and suggestions for improvements.

I designed it to use my old racing quadcopter parts.
This uses 2205 to 2306 size motors. These motors typically will deliver 1kg+ thrust each. So it should have unlimited vertical flight. It will take 5-6 inch props.
It is designed to fit a 1300-1500mah 4 cell battery, 3 or 4 9g servos (rudder optional) and there is a nose option to fit a Hs1177 style fpv camera.
You will need 6mm carbon tube for the wing spars, and fuselage spine. An ice cream stick ( we call it a paddlepop stick, in Australia) for the tailplanes.
Space inside is tight, and you may have to get creative to fit an fpv antenna in there.

The wing profile and area is straight from the original model, and is not optimised for RC models, so it might not have much lift. Depending on how well it goes, i may do another wing at a later stage.

This is a difficult print and you will need to have your printer calibrated. Advanced knowledge of your slicer settings is essential. Overhangs and support structures have been minimised, but you must follow the printing instructions for it to work.
Recommended printer size: 200x200x180. Might just fit on 180x180x120.

You can print the elevator and aileron hinges with flexible filament. If you use something else for the hinges, you will need to fill the gaps with something, im sure you can figure it out.

Option parts:
noseHS1177 will fit an fpv camera the same size as a HS1177.
Shortcowl allows you to grip the motor to change props.
Motormountthick has a thicker base, and is for mounting the motor with no motor cowl.
Covers for the elevator and rudder servos have a deep version, depends on your servo which will fit best.

Printer:

Malyan M150

Rafts:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Notes:

The general idea with this design is that the parts are printed hollow. Using more than one perimeter layer will add weight and is not needed, stick to one perimeter layer.

Temperature should be high (210c for PLA) and the fan should be off except for bridging and the top of thin parts. This will help layer adhesion, and is important for strength.

Nozzle: 0.4mm
Layer height 0.2mm
Retraction: 1.8-2mm, with 0.2mm extra restart distance. Only retract while crossing open spaces MUST be OFF. ALWAYS retract.
Infill: 0% unless specified. Only a couple of parts have infill.
One perimeter, support where needed.
Most of it is designed to need no support, having 45deg bridging or very short bridging.
Check parts like wings, and hatchtop, as these have hollows underneath which need support. Support from bed only, is recommended.

Most parts have at least 2 bottom layers, top layers depends on the part. Use brim as you see fit, the ailerons will need some for sure.
I think 2 bottom layers is right because it adds strength, for not much extra weight, and makes a nice bulkhead between sections, effectively strengthening the open top of the previous section. I left the ends of the support ribs open, allowing me to insert small joining dowels/pieces, thus aligning and holding the sections together.

Print settings for each part:

Motor cowls have a 1.5mm base, so at least 5 bottom layers, and 2 top, to make the base solid. Short cowls allow you to grip the motor easier while changing props

Motor mounts print solid, if you use the thick motormount, you dont use cowls as the base is 3mm thick.

Motorpod, use at least 2 top and 2 bottom layers, the top is thin and has bridging supports so should be fine. (worked ok for me) This part has a lot of strength as it holds the motor and will take most of the impact during landing.

Servopod needs 2 bottom layers. Enable support from bed for the servo space. You should get away with no top layers, as the top is quite pointy, just check the slicer results to be sure.

Wing, 2 bottom layers and no top. The top is open. Support for the small hollow underneath.
Inboard wing, same as wing.

Ailerons may use up to 7 bottom layers and at least 2 top layers, or 6 bottom and 3 top, this makes the servo control horn solid as it is 2mm thick. Because the first layer is 0.3mm, a total of 9 layers should be enough. You will need some brim to hold it up.

Wingtip, 2 bottom layers and 2 or 3 top. as long as you can get it to close up on top the minimum layers possible is best. Being a small part this is easy to experiment with.

Nose, 2 bottom layers and 2 or 3 top, like the wingtip, its just as long as it closes up and looks ok.

Front was originally designed to have about 3 or 4 bottom layers, but it doesnt really matter, 1 or 2 would be fine. No top layer.

Middle, this is the part that holds the wing spars and i think it needs at least 4 bottom layers. This makes the bulkhead and reinforcing strong. No top layer. Middle has short enough holes for the carbon tube to enable you to easily remove the support afterwards, if you want support in there.

Hatch top and bottom need support enabled. Minimum infill and top layers to achieve a nice looking surface. I used 10% and 3 top layers, 2 bottom and 2 perimeter. If you can do it with less, it will be lighter. The angled cutout at the rear of hatchtop is for magnets.

Rear1servo is for no rudder, elevator only. Yaw can be applied with differential thrust. Rear2servo is for a rudder tail. Enable support for the servo cutout, and 2 bottom layers with no top. I think a rudder srevo will make it tail heavy, probably best to keep it simple and have no rudder.

The little blocks that fit over the end of the servos- elevservocover and rudderservocover, i have not printed these yet. The goal is minimum weight with a good looking exterior surface.

Tail has 2 bottom layers and one top. I may develop this part to allow a paddle pop stick to brace the tailplane from inside. Depends if it needs it, we will have to fly it and see.

Tail and tailplanes, 2 bottom layers, and no top layers are needed as they are quite pointy. Rudder needs no support, but it needs that total of 9 top/bottom layers like the ailerons.

Elevator, enable support, 2 bottom layers and 1 top. It wouldnt need a top layer except for the servo control horn needs to be strong.

Assemble the motors and esc's first. Im putting the esc's in the motorpod, there is a duct for cooling. Make sure you have enough length on the cables to make it into the fuselage. Dont forget to center your servos.
Run the cables through the duct in the wing into the fuselage. Do the same for the servo cable.
When assembling the fuselage, glue the joiner pieces in the open ends of the reinforcing ribs, to align and strengthen the plane. The wingtips use these to join to the wing.
If you have trouble inserting the carbon tubes, drill the holes very carefully with a 6mm bit. Put the drill on screwdriver mode and reduce the clutch to the minimum, hold the piece so you can let go if the drillbit catches. Drill slowly.

Good luck, and dont forget to leave some feedback if you have any ideas for improvement.

Kossel XXL 1000 MAGNETIC description:
This is the XXL version of the delta 3D printer. I have been building them for two years now and I am really happy with them. It has gone through many upgrades and changes and now really works for me. This version is really big, fast and quite compared to other printers. It is good starting point to learn how 3D printing proces works. Than one could do many upgrades to it.

PRINTER SIZE:
Build volume is a cylinder. XXL of course has way bigger print width than Kossel XL.
Kossel Mini is a joke when you it next to it. :)
Personally I thing it is good idea to go for XL or XXL size.
Cost is not that higher and you have way more freedom when choosing what to print.
With Mini I always ran out of room for real life prints.

BUILD SIZE:
Standard glass diameter is 380mm.
Max print size is around 400 to 500mm depending on the rods lenght.

MANUALS:
With the purchase you get manual for mechanical and electronics assembly in PDF format.
After putting it all together calibration needs to be done.
I did my best to make quality mind-map manual. Believe me. When you learn this you will not need auto calibration.
https://www.mindmeister.com/597460511

MAIN DESCRIPTION:

  • This is XXL version DELTA PRINTER
  • 3x vertical profiles are 4020 1000mm long
  • 12x horizontal profiles are 2020 500mm long
  • CRUCIAL PARTS ARE PRE ASSEMBLED
  • 6x magnetic rods
  • 3x carriages
  • 1x effector
  • Glass (transparent) has diameter of 380mm, 4mm
  • Magnetic rods are 475mm axis to axis
  • Magnetic joint (all joints have double magnets for extra strenth)
  • Electronics: Arduino Mega + RAMPS 1.4 + 4x DRV8825 + LCD4002 + 3x optical end stops
  • Without heated bed (can be easily added later)

IN THIS KIT YOU GET:

Printed parts

  • All the printed parts (look at the pictures)

Mechanics - ALU profiles

  • 3x 4020 Aluminium profiles 1000mm
  • 12x 2020 Aluminium profiles 500mm

Mechanics

  • 6m GT2 belt
  • 3x GT2 pulley 16teeth (goes on NEMA17 shaft)
  • 6x F623ZZ bearing for belt guidance on top
  • 3x GT2 belt tensioner (spring)
  • 1x MK8 extruder parts
  • 6x rods/arms magnetic
  • 9x wheels for carriages
  • 1x hot-end for 1,75mm fillament, with PVC tube (6/4mm), 0.4mm nozzle
  • 1x glass - 380mm diameter - WHITE COLOR!
  • 3x springs to help magnets hold effector and carriage together

Motors

  • 4x NEMA17 motor 1,8degre per natural step with 1m cable with dupont connector already made
  • 3x vibration dampers for NEMA17 motors

Electrical/electronics

  • 1x ARDUINO MEGA 2560
  • 1x RAMPS 1.4
  • 4x DRV8825 stepper drivers
  • 1x LCD 2004 RepRap
  • 3x optical sensor (end stop)
  • 1x DC-DC voltage regulator for fan speed control
  • 1x power supply 12V 10A
  • 3x mini switch (if you are gonna put some lights of extra fans on printer)
  • 1x set of dupont cables
  • 1x set of dupont connectors (if you need them for any reason)
  • 1m transparent spiral cable holder (practical way of managing cables to hot end)
  • 2x spring lever cable 5 wire connector PCT-215(WAGO 222-415)
  • 3m 2 wire electrical cable
  • 1x set of nuts and bolts (60x T-nut M4 for 2020, 10x T-nut M3 for 2020, ...)

Other

  • 1x glue stick that I use
  • 1x small bottle of lubricant for magnetic joints
  • 1x tweezers
  • 1x scraper for removing prints from glass
